entry.title: Disable updatable maps in the `Libunwindstack` unwinder.
entry.content:
Updatable maps do not appear to make any positive different to

unwinding based on local testing, and we have not verified

whether they help unwinding materially during Chrome tracing.



Disabling updatable maps should (hopefully) fix crashes

(attached bug) and removed the need for additional

complexity to handle them in `ModuleCache`. No other Chrome

unwinders currently use updatable maps.



We already have trace events when unwinding fails due to a

`MAP_ERROR`, and we can use that event to study whether

we really need updatable maps in the future.



Bug: 1429916

entry.title: Rename "base::raw_ptr" into "raw_ptr".
entry.content:
The shorter form is the one to be used.

Pointers in ChromeOS ash used not to be rewritten and it is not enforced

yet. Folks started to use them, and the `base::raw_ptr` pattern emerged.



This is a fully automated patch to fix it. Script:



```

git grep -lz "base::raw_ptr<" | xargs -0 sed -i 's/base::raw_ptr
git grep -lz "base::raw_ref<" | xargs -0 sed -i 's/base::raw_ref
git checkout HEAD~ base/

git checkout HEAD~ tools/

git cl format

```

entry.title: Reland "[Office upload] Use BrowserListObserver to wait for created Files app"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 9089c92681121f77bda5c622d902dd94cc0aa80d



This is a clean reland. The failure was caused by a flaky test,

fixed in crrev.com/c/4463978, crrev.com/c/4478591



Original change's description:

> [Office upload] Use BrowserListObserver to wait for created Files app

>

> When we didn't have a Files app window to use as a modal parent for

> our dialog, we created a new Files app window and used it as the

> parent. But this didn't work because the callback we provide to

> ShowItemInFolder gets called early in the launch process, before

> the actual Files app is launched.

>

> Instead use BrowserListObserver to catch when a new Browser is

> added, check that it's the Files app window we were expecting,

> and launch our dialog with this window as the modal parent.

>

> Several tests didn't use "real" files, they just created

> FileSystemURLs to plausible locations. This meant that

> ShowItemInFolder() failed to launch Files app in tests, which

> now causes CloudOpenTask to never make progress. Use the default

> browser() in several tests to avoid this problem.

>

> Update NewModalParentCreatedWithExisting to more directly

> capture and check the Browser that was created by CloudOpenTask.

>

entry.title: [WebUI] Migrate DiagnosticsUI to WebUIConfig
entry.content:
Context:



Currently WebUI properties, e.g. CSPs, requesting schemes, host, mojo,

etc. are stored in WebUIControllers themselves or in separate lists

like IsWebUIAllowedToMakeNetworkRequests. The lifetime of a

WebUIController is bound to the frame, which makes it hard to use for

some use cases where the WebUIController hasn't been created yet. A

non-dynamically allocated class where clients could query a WebUI's

properties would be easier to use and audit.



WebUIConfig is a class that stores properties of WebUIs. For now the

properties are 1. the WebUI's origin, 2. if the WebUI is enabled,

and 3. GetURLDataSource() method for service worker initialization.

In the future this class could include information like CSPs, if we

should enable Mojo, if we should enable chrome.send(), if we should

allow network requests, URLDataSource, etc.

entry.title: [BRP/clang-plugin] emit error for raw_ptr/raw_ref pointing to a `STACK_ALLOCATED()` object
entry.content:
- Add an option `check-raw-ptr-to-stack-allocated` to the clang plugin

- When specified, `raw_ptr` or `raw_ref` pointing to "stack-allocated" objects are considered to be erroneous.

- Following existing implementation of `check-stack-allocated` rule, it can consider some classes as "stack-allocated" even if there is no explicit `STACK_ALLOCATED()` annotation. See `StackAllocatedChecker.h` for details.

- Separate `class StackAllocatedPredicate` from `class StackAllocatedChecker`.

- This will enable us to use the predicate alone for this rule.

- Modify `check-raw-ptr-fields` and `check-raw-ref-fields` rules to supreess errors for raw pointers/references to "stack-allocated" objects.

- This change is effective only if `check-raw-ptr-to-stack-allocated` is specified.

- Modify `rewrite_raw_ptr_fields` tool to follow this change

- Add `--exclude_stack_allocated` option to exclude raw pointers/references to "stack-allocated" objects from rewriting.

entry.title: [text-wrap-pretty] Move `ClearNeedsLayout` to `CreateLine`
entry.content:
Before this patch, `NGLineBreaker` calls `ClearNeedsLayout`

for empty text and fully collapsed text. It was originally in

`CollectInlines()`, crrev.com/c/1571113 moved it to

`NGLineBreaker`, but `NGLineBreaker` can be used for

computational purposes and that it shouldn't make such side

effects to the tree.



This patch moves `ClearNeedsLayout` to `CreateLine`. To do

this, empty and fully collapsed text items are appended to

`NGLineInfo` as "empty text items". They are ignored for the

layout purpose, but `CreateLine` calls `ClearNeedsLayout` for

them.



The empty text items are also needed for other use cases,

such as `text-wrap: pretty`.



This patch should have no behavior changes.
